{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":967,"record_hash":"sha256:276e28430ebf4f6fd5dd7d24e5972f6b8e872dd4aec16c1e18b4fe28fccef683","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:16:01.002Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Findings for `/Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md`:\\n\\n- **Add a non-turn environment checkpoint, or review sharing will miss the most important moment.** If the user commits / opens PR after the final agent stop hook, no new transcript records means no turn, no snapshot, no review/change index. Keep “turn = transcript capture,” but add `EnvironmentObservation` / `checkpoint` for post-agent repo state, or have review queries compare latest turn worktree files against current repo state.\\n\\n- **`hex16` turn/session keys are too short for durable identity.** A 64-bit truncated hash is fine for UI, bad for storage correctness. Use full SHA-256 or at least 128 bits. Collisions here corrupt turn identity and indexes.\\n\\n- **TurnSummary as an append-only list is not idempotent enough.** Retrying the same capture can duplicate summaries unless every writer de-dupes perfectly. Prefer `turn:<turn_key>` detail plus `turn-order = list<turn_key>` with de-dupe, or summary stored by key and ordered separately.\\n\\n- **The derived indexes should not be monolithic set values.** `branch:<key> = set<session/turn>` will grow, cause write contention, and risks lost updates if writers replace whole sets. Prefer membership keys:  \\n  `index:v1:branch:<branch-key>:<session-key>:<turn-key> = 1`  \\n  Same for review/change. Prefix scan beats giant mutable blobs.\\n\\n- **Add a commit index or remove “commit” from the promised access pattern.** The doc says review sharing can start from branch, change, commit, or PR, but v1 indexes only branch/review/change. Either add `commit:<oid> -> session/turn` or require commit queries to resolve through change ids first.\\n\\n- **PR/review keys need full namespace, not just numbers.** Store canonical review keys like `github:<host>/<owner>/<repo>#1284`, plus provider/type. PR number alone is not portable or unique.\\n\\n- **Branch keys need canonicalization beyond display name.** Store display name for humans, \n[TRUNCATED]\nd ordering semantics, first/last captured record index, and capture host/app version. Don’t rely on transcript records to imply all of that.\\n\\n- **Hash/schema versioning is missing.** Store `record_hash_version`, `turn_key_version`, and parser/source schema versions. Otherwise changing normalization later makes old records hard to compare or rebuild.\\n\\n- **Review sharing needs an explicit redaction/export layer.** Tool calls and transcripts can contain secrets, local paths, tokens, issue text, private repo context. Add storage fields or query policy for `shareable`, `redacted`, `contains_sensitive`, or make review export always pass through a redaction transform. Raw repo-access metadata is not automatically safe for web review links.\\n\\n- **Indexes must be declared rebuildable in practice, not just philosophically.** “No rebuild command in v1” is okay for a prototype, but the storage shape should include `index_version`, `built_from_schema`, and enough canonical target fields in `TurnDetail` to rebuild exactly. I’d add the rebuild command early; derived data without rebuild tooling ages badly.\\n\\n- **Normalize target observations inside TurnDetail.** Keep the rich environment snapshot, but also store a compact `observed_targets` array per turn: branch keys, review keys, change ids, commit ids. That makes verification and index rebuilding simpler and less coupled to nested stack JSON.\\n\\n- **Path evidence needs current-repo fallback.** No path index is the right call, but scoring should compare latest captured worktree paths against current queried branch/PR commits when no later turn exists. Otherwise the strongest evidence only works if another agent turn happens after the commit.\\n\\nBottom line: the hierarchy is directionally good: session owns transcript, turn owns capture evidence, indexes are accelerators. The weak spots are idempotent storage, final-state capture, key canonicalization, and review-query entry points. Fix those before implementing; they’re the parts that will hurt later.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:16:01.002Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}